Let's consider a continuous function $f : [a, b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, where $a < b$. We also have a sequence $(x_n)_{n \in \mathbb{N}}$ in $[a, b]$ that converges to a point $x \in [a, b]$. 

Assume that $f$ is differentiable at every point in $[a, b]$ except possibly at $x$. Let $f'$ denote the derivative of $f$. 

Let $F:[a, b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a function defined as follows:
\begin{align*}
F(t)=
\begin{cases}
\frac{f(t)-f(x)}{t-x}, & \text{if } t \neq x, \\
f'(x), & \text{if } t = x.
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

Show that if $F$ is continuous at $x$, then $f$ is differentiable at $x$ and $f'(x) = F(x)$.

Note: This problem is a special case of L'Hopital's rule. The challenge is to prove it without using L'Hopital's rule directly.
